    <Placemark>
        <name>#FreeNoelStephens</name>
        <description><![CDATA[
<h3>#FreeNoelStephens</h3>
<p><strong>When:</strong> Friday, September 19, 2025 at 7:00 AM UTC - 8:00 AM</p>
<p><strong>Where:</strong><br>Location not specified</p>
<p><strong>Organized by:</strong> Black Alliance for Just Immigration (BAJI)</p>
<p><strong>About:</strong></p><p>## Free Noel Stephens: Demand Immediate Release from ICE Custody

Noel Stephens is a Black bisexual Jamaican migrant currently detained by U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE). On January 29, 2026, Noel attended a scheduled annual check-in at the San Bernardino ICE Facility, as he had consistently done in compliance with his immigration requirements. During this routine appointment, he was unexpectedly taken into custody.

He is currently being held at the Adelanto ICE Processing Center. Since his detention, he has been transferred multiple times — first from Adelanto to the Arizona Removal Operations Coordination Center (AROCC) on February 7, 2026, then to the Pine Prairie ICE Processing Center on February 10, 2026, and then back to AROCC on February 19, 2026 — before being returned to Adelanto on February 21, 2026. These transfers have caused instability and disruption to his access to medical care, legal support, and family contact.

**We demand that Noel is immediately granted habeas and released from ICE Custody.**

Noel is originally from Jamaica. He entered the United States on August 17, 1997, at 22 years old, seeking safety and opportunity. Noel eventually adjusted his status to Legal Permanent Resident (LPR / Green Card) in 2004.

From 2019 until April 2024, Noel was detained for nearly four years, during which he was repeatedly shuffled between detention facilities across the country. On April 4, 2024, an immigration judge granted him protection under the Convention Against Torture (CAT), recognizing that he would face serious harm if returned to Jamaica. 

Despite having this legal protection, complying with ICE’s check-in requirements, and his long-standing ties to the United States, ICE detained Noel again at a routine check-in without explanation. ICE is now threatening to illegally deport Noel back to Jamaica. On February 8, Noel filed a habeas corpus petition challenging his unlawful detention and he is now waiting for the judge to rule in his case.  

***Black immigrant lives must not be treated as disposable.***


### Sign now to stand with Noel and demand his immediate release back to his family and community.</p>
<p><a href="https://www.mobilize.us/event/914677/" target="_blank">View Event on Mobilize.us</a></p>
<p><i>Data source: mobilize.us | Updated: 2026-03-25T07:02:17.763Z</i></p>
]]></description>
